1.Regression:
Regression is a machine learning techniques used to predict the continuous numerical values. 
Example: salary prediction, Prizes, discounts etc…
How Regression Works

Training Data
(Input + Numerical Output)                        
          ↓
Train the Regression Model
          ↓
Model Learns Relationship
          ↓
New Input
          ↓
Predict Numerical Value

	(Real-Life Example 2: Salary Prediction
	Experience	Salary
	1 year	₹4 LPA
	2 years	₹6 LPA
	3 years	₹8 LPA
	New employee:
	Experience = 2.5 years
	Prediction:
	Salary ≈ ₹7 LPA)
	

Regression is a type of supervised learning used to predict continuous numerical values. It learns the relationship between input features and a numerical target variable, then uses that relationship to predict values for new data.
										  Types of Regressions:
Regression
 │
├── 1. Linear Regression
├── 2. Multiple Linear Regression
├── 3. Polynomial Regression
├── 4. Ridge Regression
├── 5. Lasso Regression
 └── 6. Elastic Net Regression

1.Linear Regression:    predicts a continuous value by understand the  relationship between the input and the output.  
When to Use
	• House Price Prediction 
	• Salary Prediction 
	• Sales Prediction
	
2. Multiple Linear Regression:  Multiple Linear Regression predicts the output using more than one input feature.  It is an extension of Linear Regression.
When to Use
	• House price prediction with multiple features 
	• Employee salary prediction 
	• Medical cost prediction
	
3. Polynomial Regression: is used when the relationship between the input and output  It is useful for non-linear relationships.
Applications
	• Population growth 
	• Temperature prediction 
	• Stock trend analysis (in some cases) 
	
4. Ridge Regression(L2):  version of Linear Regression that uses L2 Regularization.
Example
A house price dataset contains many related features such as:
	• Area 
	• Number of rooms 
	• Floor area 
	• Balcony size 
Ridge Regression reduces overfitting while still using all these features.

5. Lasso Regression(L1): Lasso Regression automatically removes the unnecessary 35 features and builds a simpler model. It reduces overfitting and automatically removes less important features by making some coefficients exactly zero.
 
Why Use Lasso Regression?
Suppose you have 100 features.
Not all of them are useful.
Lasso helps by:
	• Removing unnecessary features. 
	• Making the model simpler. 
	• Reducing overfitting. 
	• Improving prediction on new data. 
	
6. Elastic Net Regression: Elastic Net Regression combines both L1 (Lasso) and L2 (Ridge) regularization. It reduces overfitting while also selecting important features. It works well when many input features are correlated. 
 → Overfitting = Memorization, not Understanding

• L1 = Feature Selection (removes some features). 
• L2 = Coefficient Shrinking (keeps all features but reduces their impact). 
• Elastic Net = Combination of L1 and L2.
